  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Superficial epidermal infection characterized by amber crusts (nonbullous) or vesicles (bullous)\nMay be super-infection or primary infection\nTypical causative organisms are\nStaphylococcus aureus\nor\nStreptococcus pyogenes\nFever and systemic signs are uncommon\nPost-streptococcal glomerular nephritis\nis a possible complication, and incidence is not reduced by antibiotic therapy\nHighly contagious and easily transmittable",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "Staphylococcus aureus",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Staphylococcus_aureus"
        },
        {
          "text": "Streptococcus pyogenes",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Streptococcus_pyogenes"
        },
        {
          "text": "Post-streptococcal glomerular nephritis",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Post-streptococcal_glomerular_nephritis"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "Nonbullous\nErythematous macules/papules develop into vesicles which become pustular and rupture\nAs rupture release yellow fluid which dries to form stratified golden crust\nBullous\nBullae form as result of staph toxin\nSome cases caused by\nMRSA\nUncommonly painful, but usually pruritic\nRegional\nlymphadenopathy\nis common",
      "subsections": {},
